%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Introduction}
%******************************************************************************

The goal of this book is to present in full details the source code of
a few {profilers}.

\section{Motivations}

Why a profiler? Because I think you are a better programmer if
you fully understand how things work under the hood.

%claude:
Indeed, writing correct code is only half the job---making it
fast enough is the other half.
A profiler tells you \emph{where} your program actually spends
its time, replacing guesswork with measurement.
Without a profiler, programmers often optimize the wrong
function, or worse, make the code harder to read for no
measurable gain.
As the saying goes: ``premature optimization is the root
of all evil''~(Knuth), but \emph{informed} optimization,
guided by profiling data, is simply good engineering.

%claude:
Moreover, understanding how a profiler works gives you
insight into the interplay between user programs, the
compiler toolchain, and the kernel.
A profiler like [[prof]] relies on the linker to
instrument function calls, while [[tprof]] relies on
the kernel to sample the program counter at regular
intervals.
Studying these tools therefore ties together concepts
from \book{Linker} and \book{Kernel}.

Here are a few questions I hope this book will answer:
\begin{itemize}

\item How do you measure the time spent by a program?
What is the difference between {user time}, {system time},
and {real time} (wall-clock time)?

\item How does a {sampling profiler} work?
How does the kernel periodically record where a program
is executing?

\item How does an {instrumenting profiler} work?
What code does the linker insert at function entry and exit
to record call counts and timing?

\item How can you trace system calls and visualize
system-wide activity in real time?

\item What is the role of the [[/proc]] filesystem
and the [[TOS]] (Top of Stack) structure in supporting
profiling on \plan?

\end{itemize}

\section{The \plan profilers: [[prof]], [[tprof]], [[trace]], [[stats]]}
% and kprof, and iostats

% as opposed to most books in principia, here a collection of programs.
% why so many?

%claude:
Unlike most books in \principia, which focus on a single program
(one assembler, one linker, one shell), this book covers a
\emph{collection} of small profiling tools.
The reason is that profiling is not a single problem but a
spectrum: you might want to time an entire command ([[time]]),
identify which functions are hot ([[prof]], [[tprof]]),
trace individual system calls ([[trace]]),
monitor system-wide resource usage ([[stats]]),
or measure the I/O cost of a file server ([[iostats]]).
Each tool addresses a different point on that spectrum,
and each is small enough---a few hundred lines of C---that
together they still form a manageable codebase.

%claude:
Like for most books in \principia, I chose \plan programs because
those programs are simple, small, elegant, open source, and they
form together a coherent set.
The \plan profilers total roughly 3000 lines of code,
compared to the tens of thousands of lines in Linux's [[perf]]
tool alone.

\section{Other profilers}

Here are a few profilers that I considered for this book, but 
which I ultimately discarded:
\begin{itemize}

%history:
% ?? prof?

\item [[gprof]]~\cite{gprof} is the classic \unix profiler.
%claude:
It combines instrumentation (the compiler inserts code at each
function entry to record call arcs) with statistical sampling
(the kernel periodically interrupts the program to record its
program counter). The combination gives both call counts and
time estimates per function.
[[gprof]] was introduced with 4.2BSD and became the standard
profiling tool on \unix systems for decades.
The \plan [[prof]] tool works on a similar principle but is
simpler, relying on the linker rather than the compiler for
instrumentation.

\item OProfile is a system-wide statistical profiler for Linux
that uses hardware {performance counters} when available.
% dean?
%claude:
Unlike [[gprof]], which requires recompiling the target program,
OProfile can profile any running program, including the kernel
itself, with low overhead.

\item [[perf]] is the modern Linux profiling framework.
% huge on Linux
% perf for haskell profiling:
% https://www.fpcomplete.com/user/bitonic/perf-for-low-level-profiling
% http://jvns.ca/blog/2016/03/12/how-does-perf-work-and-some-questions/
%claude:
It subsumes most of what OProfile and [[gprof]] do, and
adds tracing, hardware counter access, and visualization.
However, the [[perf]] codebase is enormous---tens of thousands
of lines of C---making it unsuitable for a teaching book.

\end{itemize}

