\section{Profiler principles}

%Jon Bentley's toy profiler
% see programming pearl
%see also my profiling OCaml poor's man profiler -profile!

%See profiler section in Kernel.nw
%lib_core/libc/profile.c!! tos.h!!

% see include/libc.h prof() and enum prof

%back of the enveloppe:
% - see jeff's dean big number everyone should now
% - http://www.eecs.berkeley.edu/~rcs/research/interactive_latency.html

%claude:
There are two fundamental approaches to profiling.
The first is {instrumentation}: the toolchain (compiler or
linker) inserts extra code at each function entry and exit to
record call counts and elapsed time. This is what \plan's
[[prof]] does---the linker [[5l -p]] inserts calls to
[[_profin]] and [[_profout]] around every function.
The result is a precise call tree with exact counts, but
the overhead can be significant.

%claude:
The second approach is {sampling}: the kernel periodically
interrupts the running program (typically on each clock tick)
and records its current program counter. After enough
samples, the histogram reveals where the program spends
most of its time. This is what [[tprof]] does, via the
[[/proc/\emph{pid}/profile]] file. Sampling has low overhead
but gives only statistical estimates---it cannot tell you
how many times a function was called, only how often the
CPU was found executing within it.

%claude:
The \plan profiling tools also include a third category:
{tracing} and {monitoring}. [[trace]] shows real-time
scheduler events (process switches, deadlines, releases)
in a graphical timeline, while [[stats]] displays rolling
graphs of system-wide counters (syscalls/sec, context
switches, memory usage, etc.). These tools do not profile
a single program but rather observe the whole system.





%\section{[[time]] command-line interface}

\section{[[prof]] and [[tprof]] command-line interfaces}
%\section{[[kprof]] command-line interface}

%claude:
[[prof]] reads a profile data file ([[prof.\emph{pid}]])
produced by an instrumented program and correlates it with
the program's symbol table. For each function, it prints
the percentage of time spent there, the absolute time, and
the call count. The [[-d]] flag prints the dynamic call
graph instead, showing the tree of calls indented by depth.

%claude:
[[tprof]] works differently: it reads
[[/proc/\emph{pid}/profile]], which contains
interrupt-time samples of the program counter collected
by the kernel. Since sampling cannot track calls,
[[tprof]] has no [[-d]] (call graph) option---it only
reports time per function.
To enable sampling, you first write ``[[profile]]'' to
[[/proc/\emph{pid}/ctl]], let the program run, then
run [[tprof \emph{pid}]] while the process is still alive.

%claude:
[[kprof]] is a variant of [[prof]] that profiles the
kernel itself. It reads the data accumulated by the
[[kprof(3)]] device ([[/dev/kpdata]]), which records
one count per clock tick per 8-byte range of kernel text.

\section{[[trace]] and [[stats]] graphical user interfaces}

%claude:
[[trace]] and [[stats]] are graphical programs that display
system activity in real time.
[[trace]] reads events from [[/proc/trace]] and draws a
timeline for each traced process: colored blocks show
when a process is running, and arrows mark scheduling
events (releases, deadlines, yields, overruns).
The user can zoom in and out with [[+]]/[[-]] and pause
with [[p]].

%claude:
[[stats]] reads counters from kernel pseudo-files
([[#c/sysstat]], [[#c/swap]], [[/net/ether0/0/stats]])
and plots rolling graphs updated once per second.
It can display dozens of metrics: system load, memory
usage, context switches, syscalls, interrupts, TLB
misses, network packets, and more. It can even monitor
multiple machines simultaneously, drawing their graphs
in adjacent columns.

<<function usage (misc/stats.c)>>=
void
usage(void)
{
    fprint(2, "usage: stats [-O] [-S scale] [-LY] [-%s] [machine...]\n", argchars);
    exits("usage");
}
@

\section{[[iostats]] filesystem interface}

%claude:
[[iostats]] takes yet another approach: it is a
user-level {file server} that interposes itself between a
program and the regular file server, intercepting all 9P
messages. When the program exits, [[iostats]] prints a
report showing how much data was read and written, the
number and latency of each 9P message type, and a
per-file I/O summary.
This is a classic \plan design: instead of adding
tracing hooks inside the kernel, you insert a proxy file
server in the namespace.
%
For example, [[iostats ls]] runs [[ls]] through the
proxy and reports how many [[read]], [[stat]], and
[[open]] messages that simple command generates.

\section{Profiling [[hello]]}

% time
% prof
% tprof
% trace
% stats
% iostats

%claude:
To get a feel for the tools, consider profiling the simplest
possible program, [[hello]]. With [[time]], you would run:
\begin{verbatim}
  time hello
\end{verbatim}
and see something like [[0.00u 0.00s 0.01r]]---user time,
system time, and real (wall-clock) time, all in seconds.
%
With [[prof]], you would first link [[hello]] with
[[-p]] to enable instrumentation, run it to produce a
[[prof.\emph{pid}]] file, then run [[prof hello]] to see
which functions were called and how long they took.
%
With [[tprof]], you would start [[hello]] (or a
longer-running variant), enable profiling via
[[/proc/\emph{pid}/ctl]], and then run
[[tprof \emph{pid}]] to see the sampling histogram.
%
With [[iostats hello]], you would see the 9P messages
generated by [[hello]]'s call to [[write]] on
[[/dev/cons]].

